\f0\b\fs36 Defining Section Types\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 The above is all a little abstract. It will make much more sense if we think about this in terms of the current binder and set up some custom section types ourselves. Take a look at the contents of the Draft folder in the binder:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The three folders at the top level of the Draft folder are \'93The Basics\'94, \'93Going Further\'94 and \'93Tips\'94\'97the three folders that use custom yellow icons (by \'93top level\'94, I mean the ones that are indented the least). The way I\'92ve organised this tutorial, each of these folders represents a major 
\i part
\i0  of the Draft.\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The blue folders inside the three top-level folders\'97folders such as \'93Get Oriented\'94, \'93Get Organised\'94 and so on\'97are essentially 
\i chapters
\i0 .\
{\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}The text documents inside the blue folders each represent a different 
\i section
\i0  inside a chapter.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 So, the way I have organised the Draft for this tutorial is by parts, chapters and sections. Let\'92s set up the section types of this project to reflect that.\

