\f3\i\b Tip: 
\f2\i0\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::1>
\f0\fs28 You can open these instructions in a separate window so that you can read them while the Project Settings panel is open by clicking on the yellow pencil button in the toolbar. This opens a \'93Quick Reference\'94 window which you can place alongside the main project window. If there isn\'92t room on your screen for both windows, go to Window > Float Quick Reference Panels. This will ensure the Quick Reference window floats over the top of the main project window.\cell \lastrow\row
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}In the main menu, go to 
\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_Cs::2>
\f3\b Project > Project Settings\'85
\f2\b0 \cf0 <!$Scr_Cs::2>
\f0\fs28  and make sure \'93Section Types\'94 is selected in the list on the left of the window that appears.\
{\listtext	2.	}In the \'93Section Types\'94 tab, double-click into \'93Heading\'94 and change its title to \'93Part\'94.\
{\listtext	3.	}Do the same for \'93Text\'94, renaming it to \'93Chapter\'94.\
{\listtext	4.	}Click the \'93+\'94 button to add a third section type and name it \'93Section\'94. (Note that you can drag and drop section types in this list to reorder them, but we\'92ll leave this order as-is.)\
{\listtext	5.	}Click \'93OK\'94.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Now click on the section type pop-up menu in the inspector again. You\'92ll see that where before there were options for \'93Heading\'94 and \'93Text\'94, there are now options for \'93Part\'94, \'93Chapter\'94 and \'93Section\'94, which makes much more sense for our project.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl264\slmult1\sb300\sa120\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf2 <$Scr_H::1><$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\b\fs36 Defining Default Section Types by Structure\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 <!$Scr_H::1><!$Scr_Ps::0>
\f0\fs28 There\'92s a problem, however: this document is shown as being a \'93Chapter\'94 rather than a \'93Section\'94. One way we could fix this would be to override the setting manually. Try that now:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Click on the section type pop-up menu in the inspector.\
{\listtext	2.	}Change the setting to \'93Section\'94.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Great! Except\'85 It\'92s going to be a pain to change that setting for every single text document in the binder. Fortunately, we don\'92t have to. Let\'92s change it back again:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Once more, click on the section type pop-up.\
{\listtext	2.	}Change the setting to \'93Structure-Based\'94. (It will change back to \'93Chapter\'94 in italicised text.)\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'93Structure-Based\'94 means: 
\i Use a default section type based on the indentation of this document in the binder
\i0 . But how does Scrivener pick a section type based on indentation? That\'92s something you teach it in the Project Settings again:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Open the Project Settings from the main menu again.\
{\listtext	2.	}This time, select the \'93Default Types by Structure\'94 tab at the top. As soon as you do, you\'92ll notice that many folders in the binder are highlighted yellow.\
{\listtext	3.	}Try clicking on the three rows\'97\'93All folders\'94, \'93All file groups\'94 and \'93All files\'94. As you do so, different documents will be highlighted yellow in the binder.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The yellow highlights show which documents are affected by the selected setting. So, when you select \'93All folders\'94, all folders are highlighted yellow, for instance. Now let\'92s change the default settings:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Leave \'93All folders\'94 as it is for now (so that the \'93Section Type\'94 is set to \'93Part\'94).\
{\listtext	2.	}Change the section type for \'93All file groups\'94 to \'93Section\'94. (A file group is a text document containing other text documents.)\
{\listtext	3.	}Change the section type for \'93All files\'94 to \'93Section\'94.\
{\listtext	4.	}Click \'93OK\'94.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 We just told Scrivener that all folders are parts and all text documents are sections. If you look over in the inspector again, you\'92ll see that the section type for this document now correctly reads \'93Section\'94. If you click on any other text document, you\'92ll also see the section type set as \'93Section\'94. If you click on a folder, such as \'93The Basics\'94 or \'93Get Oriented\'94, you\'92ll see the section type set as \'93Part\'94.\
But wait, we don\'92t want 
\i all
\i0  folders to be parts\'97only the top-level folders in the Draft (the ones using custom yellow icons) should be parts. The folders inside them (one level deeper) should be chapters. Let\'92s fix that:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	1.	}Open Project Settings again.\
{\listtext	2.	}Click on \'93All folders\'94 to select it.\
{\listtext	3.	}Click the \'93+\'94 button (the one with two lines next to it).\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	4.	}Note how \'93All folders\'94 changes to \'93Root folders\'94 and another row is added entitled \'93Level 1 folders and deeper\'94.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1440\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	5.	}Click the \'93+\'94 button again.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1120\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	6.	}A \'93Level 2 folders and deeper\'94 row will be added.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\tx1440\li720\fi-720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	7.	}Try selecting the different folder settings\'97\'93Root folders\'94, \'93Level 1 folders\'94 and \'93Level 2 folders and deeper\'94\'97and take notice of what gets highlighted in the binder. You\'92ll see that the Draft folder is a \'93root folder\'94, the yellow folders are at \'93level 1\'94, and the folders using regular blue icons are at \'93level 2\'94.\
{\listtext	8.	}Change the section type for \'93Level 2 folders and deeper\'94 to \'93Chapter\'94.\
{\listtext	9.	}Click \'93OK\'94.\
\pard\tx720\sl264\slmult1\sa360\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Now try clicking on \'93The Basics\'94 and \'93Get Oriented\'94 in the binder again, taking note of the section type for each in the inspector, before returning here. Scrivener now knows how our binder is structured, and what each level represents. This means that, from now on, we\'92ll only need to change the section type in the inspector for the occasional document that we want to be different.\

